## 4. Reform Efforts and Integration

### 4.1 Chinese Higher Education Reform

Chinaâ€™s **Development Plan (2010-2020)** aims to relax central control, grant universities autonomy, diversify admission criteria beyond Gaokao, and increase government funding to 4% of GDP by 2012. The plan encourages institutions to design reform programs tailored to their needs ([UKEssays, 2018](https://www.ukessays.com/essays/education/comparison-on-higher-education-between-china-and-america-education-essay.php?vref=1)).

### 4.2 American Higher Education Reform

The U.S. government, under President Obama, initiated reforms to **control rising college costs**, improve affordability and value, promote completion rates, and provide better data for families choosing colleges. Initiatives include reallocating federal aid, incentivizing cost control, and supporting innovation in teaching ([The White House, 2012](https://obamawhitehouse.archives.gov/the-press-office/2012/01/27/fact-sheet-president-s-plan-higher-education-reform)).

### 4.3 Integration and Collaboration

China has increasingly studied and adopted aspects of American curriculum and instructional systems, exemplified by joint ventures like New York University and Duke University campuses in Shanghai. Conversely, the U.S. is encouraged to consider new approaches in response to Chinaâ€™s rapid expansion in higher education quality and quantity ([UKEssays, 2018](https://www.ukessays.com/essays/education/comparison-on-higher-education-between-china-and-america-education-essay.php?vref=1)).

